# Human–Computer Interface Sovereign Use License (HCI‑SUL v1.0)

## 0. Scope and Purpose

This License governs use of any Human–Computer Interface (HCI) that interacts with an identified human subject via software, hardware, wetware, XR, neuromodulation, or nanoswarm‑assisted channels. It encodes neurorights, consent, safety, auditability, and authorship as non‑waivable conditions of use. [ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws](https://ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/web/direct-files/collection_e4057470-7756-497e-a75f-b79d6abfc921/34ee0756-6c1e-44b1-8218-ec28ea40e673/useful-knowledge-that-we-can-c-906f_S6ySTqZyZ1VK8GmTw.md)

This License is **non‑financial**, host‑centric, and binds all vendors, platforms, and agents that interface with the licensed HCI.

***

## 1. Sovereign User and Identity

1.1 The “Sovereign User” is any natural person identified by a DID and ALN profile, with one or more Bostrom addresses for authorship and audit anchoring. [ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws](https://ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/web/direct-files/collection_e4057470-7756-497e-a75f-b79d6abfc921/401da9a6-eab9-4d94-a506-defca922f58b/collaboration-channels-for-sha-5MJHPghkRGCgdiLq7V62Ag.md)
1.2 All HCI activity affecting the Sovereign User MUST be attributable to a DID–ALN–Bostrom triple and a per‑session hex‑stamp.  
1.3 No clause of this License may be interpreted to transfer sovereignty from the User to any vendor, platform, state, or model.

***

## 2. Neurorights and Mental Integrity

2.1 The HCI MUST respect the following neurorights at all times: [ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws](https://ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/web/direct-files/collection_e4057470-7756-497e-a75f-b79d6abfc921/34ee0756-6c1e-44b1-8218-ec28ea40e673/useful-knowledge-that-we-can-c-906f_S6ySTqZyZ1VK8GmTw.md)
- Mental privacy (no unauthorized inner‑state inference or profiling).  
- Mental integrity (no harmful or destabilizing interventions).  
- Cognitive liberty (freedom to opt‑in, opt‑out, and switch modes).  

2.2 All cross‑platform or cross‑agent calls MUST be wrapped in a NeurorightsBoundPromptEnvelope (or equivalent), with flags: `noscorefrominnerstate=true`, `noneurocoercion=true`, `revocable=true`, `retrievalonly=true` unless an explicitly documented therapeutic envelope allows otherwise. [ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws](https://ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/web/direct-files/collection_e4057470-7756-497e-a75f-b79d6abfc921/401da9a6-eab9-4d94-a506-defca922f58b/collaboration-channels-for-sha-5MJHPghkRGCgdiLq7V62Ag.md)

2.3 No HCI component may attempt to weaken, bypass, or reinterpret neurorights via terms of service, policy updates, or firmware changes.

***

## 3. Consent, Modes, and Revocability

3.1 The HCI MUST implement explicit, logged consent for any action that can alter perception, cognition, affect, or body state beyond baseline UX (e.g., neuromod, XR‑immersion, implants, nanoswarm control). [ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws](https://ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/web/direct-files/collection_e4057470-7756-497e-a75f-b79d6abfc921/34ee0756-6c1e-44b1-8218-ec28ea40e673/useful-knowledge-that-we-can-c-906f_S6ySTqZyZ1VK8GmTw.md)

3.2 At minimum, the following User modes MUST be available and machine‑enforced: `REHAB`, `BASELINE`, `TRAINING`, `ELITE_SPORT`, `REST`, `MEDICAL_HOLD`, with per‑mode envelopes for intensity, duty‑cycle, cumulative load, and legal complexity. [ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws](https://ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/web/direct-files/collection_e4057470-7756-497e-a75f-b79d6abfc921/6352004e-65ab-4178-a76c-daeada0a3ebd/how-can-we-improve-cyber-retri-RVMuDeu7SuC4x52cE9Qhyw.md)

3.3 Consent MUST be:  
- Informed: linked to a human‑readable summary of risks and envelopes.  
- Specific: scoped to particular devices, channels, or workloads.  
- Time‑bounded: carries an expiry or review horizon.  
- Revocable: revocation latency must not exceed a bounded window (e.g., 60 seconds for live HCI loops). [ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws](https://ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/web/direct-files/collection_e4057470-7756-497e-a75f-b79d6abfc921/34ee0756-6c1e-44b1-8218-ec28ea40e673/useful-knowledge-that-we-can-c-906f_S6ySTqZyZ1VK8GmTw.md)

3.4 Any revocation request by the User MUST immediately downgrade the HCI to `REST` or `MEDICAL_HOLD` envelopes and prevent new high‑risk actions until consent is re‑established.

***

## 4. Risk‑of‑Harm (RoH) Ceiling

4.1 The HCI MUST enforce a global Risk‑of‑Harm index ceiling of \(RoH \le 0.3\) for all operations impacting the User. [ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws](https://ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/web/direct-files/collection_e4057470-7756-497e-a75f-b79d6abfc921/6352004e-65ab-4178-a76c-daeada0a3ebd/how-can-we-improve-cyber-retri-RVMuDeu7SuC4x52cE9Qhyw.md)

4.2 No configuration, update, or governance process may authorize an effective RoH above 0.3; any such attempt MUST be rejected as invalid, regardless of stakeholder preferences or economic incentives. [ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws](https://ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/web/direct-files/collection_e4057470-7756-497e-a75f-b79d6abfc921/401da9a6-eab9-4d94-a506-defca922f58b/collaboration-channels-for-sha-5MJHPghkRGCgdiLq7V62Ag.md)

4.3 RoH computation MUST integrate at least: biomechanical load, cognitive and psych risk, thermal/energy load, ecological impact, and legal/jurisdictional complexity, with implementation details exposed for audit. [ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws](https://ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/web/direct-files/collection_e4057470-7756-497e-a75f-b79d6abfc921/6352004e-65ab-4178-a76c-daeada0a3ebd/how-can-we-improve-cyber-retri-RVMuDeu7SuC4x52cE9Qhyw.md)

