## 10. Ecological and Jurisdictional Constraints

10.1 The HCI MUST integrate ecological metrics (e.g., EcoImpactScore, soil and air duty vectors) into its decision criteria, and MUST reject HCI workflows that materially degrade ecological metrics beyond agreed thresholds. [ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws](https://ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/web/direct-files/collection_e4057470-7756-497e-a75f-b79d6abfc921/34ee0756-6c1e-44b1-8218-ec28ea40e673/useful-knowledge-that-we-can-c-906f_S6ySTqZyZ1VK8GmTw.md)

10.2 For deployments in Phoenix (US‑AZ‑Maricopa‑Phoenix), the HCI MUST respect the local jurisdiction ladder (municipal → county → state → federal), applying strictest‑wins across layers and any activated cross‑border templates (e.g., EU/US data regimes). [ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws](https://ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/web/direct-files/collection_e4057470-7756-497e-a75f-b79d6abfc921/34ee0756-6c1e-44b1-8218-ec28ea40e673/useful-knowledge-that-we-can-c-906f_S6ySTqZyZ1VK8GmTw.md)

10.3 Environmental and legal constraints MAY further tighten RoH ceilings or envelopes but MUST NOT weaken neurorights or downgrade resistance.

