## 12. Enforcement and Remedies

12.1 The HCI MUST expose verifiable interfaces for third‑party auditors (including the User) to check:  
- Current neurorights profile,  
- Active envelopes and RoH ceilings,  
- Recent RopeSteps and hex‑stamps,  
- Rights Kernel configuration and Eibon continuity shard state. [ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws](https://ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/web/direct-files/collection_e4057470-7756-497e-a75f-b79d6abfc921/401da9a6-eab9-4d94-a506-defca922f58b/collaboration-channels-for-sha-5MJHPghkRGCgdiLq7V62Ag.md)

12.2 Upon detection of a violation, the system MUST:  
- Immediately route to `MEDICAL_HOLD` envelopes,  
- Halt non‑essential high‑risk HCI functions,  
- Preserve all logs and evidence,  
- Present the User with a human‑readable summary of the violation and options for rollback or vendor termination. [ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws](https://ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/web/direct-files/collection_e4057470-7756-497e-a75f-b79d6abfc921/401da9a6-eab9-4d94-a506-defca922f58b/collaboration-channels-for-sha-5MJHPghkRGCgdiLq7V62Ag.md)

12.3 Continued use of the HCI after a proven violation requires explicit User re‑consent and documented remediation of the defect.

